04049nam a2200541Ia 9781438479859DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384798597 a10.1515/97814384798592doi  a(DE-B1597)681548  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041002bisacsh04a861.5qOCoLC223/eng/2023021600aJosé María Heredia in New York, 1823–1825 :bAn Exiled Cuban Poet in the Age of Revolution, Selected Letters and Verse /ced. by Frederick Luciani. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (286 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSelected Letters, 1823–1825 -- tSelected Verse, 1823–1825 -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume offers the most complete English translation to date of the prose and poetry of José María Heredia (b. Cuba, 1803; d. Mexico, 1839), focusing on Heredia's political exile in the United States from November 1823 to August 1825. Frederick Luciani's introduction offers a complete biographical sketch that discusses the complications of Heredia's life in exile, his conflicted political views, his significance as a travel writer and observer of life in the United States, and his reception by nineteenth-century North American writers and critics. The volume includes thoroughly annotated letters that Heredia wrote to family and friends in Cuba, describing his struggles and adventures living among other young expatriates in New York City—fellow conspirators in a failed plot to overthrow Spanish rule on the island. His travel letters, especially those that describe his trip to the Niagara frontier in 1824 along the Hudson River and the Erie Canal, offer discerning reflections on American landscapes, technological advances, political culture, and social customs. The volume also offers translations of the verse that Heredia composed during his New York exile, in which he gave impassioned voice to Cuba's struggle for independence from Spain, and which reflected the emerging Romantic sensibilities in Spanish-language poetry. With accurate, clear translations, this volume serves as an introduction to a figure who is enshrined in the canon of Latin American literature, but scarcely known to Anglophone readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPoets, Cubany19th centuryvBiography. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aLiterature : Nineteenth-Century Studies. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aLuciani, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuciani, Frederick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847985940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438479859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438479859/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles